<h3>
    Using an Light-Emitting Diode (LED)
</h3>

<ul>
    <li>
        Look carefully at the two metal prongs on the diode.
        One is slightly longer than the other.
        For the diode to light...
        <ul>
            <li>
                The <emph>longer</emph> end of the diode must be pointed towards the <emph>positive</emph> end of the battery (the anode).
            </li>
            <li>
                The <emph>negative</emph> end of the diode must be pointed towards the <emph>negative</emph> end of the battery (the cathode).
            </li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>
        The LED, when lit, provides almost not resistance.
        Therefore, if the diode is connected to the battery alone and is lit,
        you have a <emph>short circuit</emph> and the battery could potentially overheat.
        To counteract this, you should <strong>ALWAYS</strong> connect the LED <emph>in series with a resistor</emph>.
        <ul>
            <li>
                If using about 3 DC volts, for the best results, use a resistor with a resistance less than 100 Ω.
                If you use a higher resistance resistor, the current may be too low to
                get a strong light from the diode.
            </li>
        </ul>
    </li>
</ul>


