<ol>
    <li>
        Connect the battery, the diode, and the resistor in series on the breadboard.
        Make sure the diode is oriented correctly, with
        the longer prong towards the positive end of the battery.
        <!-- diagram -->
    </li>
    <li>
        The diode should light!
    </li>
    <li>
        Measure the power of the LED. To do so, measure the potential difference
        across the diode using a voltmeter, measure teh current of the
        circuit, and use the formula \( P = IV \).
        Note that:
        <ul>
            <li>
                Power is the rate at which the LED converts the chemical potential
                energy of the battery into electromagnetic (light) energy.
            </li>
            <li>
                The current is identical at all points of the circuit,
                because the circuit is in series.
            </li>
            <li>
                You cannot determine the resistance of the diode
                by using Ohm's Law ( \( V = IR \) )
                because it is not an Ohmic resistor,
                and does not follow Ohm's Law.
            </li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>
        Confirm that the diode is offering near-zero resistance.
        We cannot measure the resistance of the by using Ohm's Law
        ( \( V = IR \) )
        because it is not an Ohmic resistor,
        meaning does not follow Ohm's Law.
        However, we can confirm the resistance is very low by
        using Ohm's Law to calculate what we would expect the
        current to be if only the resistor and batteries were present,
        then comparing this to the actualy current (measured with an ammeter).
    </li>
    <li>
        Flip around the diode. It should not light.
    </li>
    <li>
        Measure the current through the diode and the voltage drop f teh diode
        in order to measure its resistance. You should get a very high value.
        (The resistance may be too high to make these measurements accurately.
        As an alternative, simply demonstrate that the current is much much less
        than would be expected if only the resistor were in the circuit.)
    </li>
</ol>


